{
  "text": "\u00b7 g a is the fraction of energy of the secondary electrons, which is lost in bremsstrahlung. The g a value of 0.001 given by DGMP task group [CITATION_1] is used in this study. \u00b7 (\u00b5 en /\u03c1) a-w is the ratio of mass energy absorption co-efficient of air to that of water. The value of (\u00b5 en /\u03c1) a-w for 192 Ir source used in this study is 0.899 . \u00b7 k Q is the beam quality correction factor, which accounts for the differences in the energy spectrum of the reference photon beam (usually 60 Co) for which the chamber has been calibrated and 192 Ir spectrum (generally determined through interpolation of calibration factor of 60 Co and highest X-ray energy available). Since the energy dependence of modern thimble chambers is marginal [CITATION_2] a value of 1.0 is used. \u00b7 k r = (1/r 0 ) 2 , where r 0 is the reference distance of 1 meter.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "23096935",
    "[CITATION_2]": "23096935"
